Hello all,

Here is a small use-case that greatly simplified glob usage in asynchronous situations: instead of checking if .found is set or not and checking if we have missed a match or two before we set the handler but before the glob is done, it would be more logical to add in some way an option to guarantee calling of the handlers with the full set of data...

In my view the best approach would be to:
- 'end' handler is guaranteed to trigger regardless of whether the handler is set before or after the search is done.
- 'match' handler is guaranteed to trigger for each match regardless whether the handler was set before of after it actually triggered.

Here is an implementation I've done for my use-case:

``` javascript
function guaranteeGlobEvents(glob, all_matches){
    all_matches = all_matches == null ? true : all_matches
    var visited = []

    return glob
        // keep track of visited matches...
        .on('match', function(path){
            all_matches && visited.push(path)
        })
        // trigger new handlers...
        .on('newListener', function(evt, func){
            // trigger the 'end' handler if we have already finished...
            if(evt == 'end' && this.found != null){
                func.call(this, this.found)

            // trigger the 'match' handler for each match already found...
            } else if(all_matches && evt == 'match' && visited.length > 0){
                var that = this
                visited.forEach(function(path){
                    func.call(that, path)
                })
            }
        })
}
```

_UPDATE: fixed a small bug in the code above..._

Basic usage:

``` javascript
var g = guaranteeGlobEvents(glob('**/*js'))

// do some stuff...

// this handler will get called for every match missed up until this point and all consecutive matches...
g.on('match', function(path){ console.log(path) })
```

An alternative to this approach would be to define a set of separate events that are guaranteed to be triggered.

NOTE: I do not insist on either this implementation nor on this interface, but IMHO an option for a guaranteed state tracking would be nice :)

P.S. Merry Christmas!

