comments.body:
@isaacs Actually the packages you mentioned are updated 9 years ago and 6 years ago. I think you know they are not really an alternative to `node-glob`.

I literally spent 1 hour and couldn't find a decent globing/find npm package with CLI.

What are your concerns about adding a CLI? Path expanding in the command prompt? Something else?

I think you probably want something that will do more than just `find`.  Because it's not like `markdownlint $(glob *.md apps/*/*.md)` or `glob *.md apps/*/*.md | xargs markdownlint` will work on windows either, because it doesn't have `xargs` or `$()`.

What about something like this?

```ts
#!/usr/bin/env node
import { globSync } from 'glob'
import { spawnSync } from 'node:child_process'
const cmd = process.argv[2]
const args = process.argv.slice(3)
  .map(a => globSync(a))
  .reduce((set: string[], a) => set.concat(a), [])
const result = spawnSync(cmd, args, {
  stdio: 'inherit',
})
if (result.exitCode) {
  process.exitCode = result.exitCode
} else if (result.signal) {
  process.kill(process.pid, result.signal)
  setTimeout(() => {}, 200)
}
```

Then you could run `glob markdownlint *.md apps/*/*.md`.  On cmd or powershell, it'd expand the args, and on bash, it'd just be a no-op, since the args would already be expanded.

Of course, this gets weird if some of the filenames have special glob characters.  For example, if you had a file like `app/routes/[id].tsx`, then it'd be expanded by bash, and then try to expand it in glob, and would match `app/routes/i.tsx` and `app/routes/d.tsx`, which is not what you want.

I'm not really aware of a surefire way to _know_ whether we've been executed in cmd.exe vs bash (process.platform isn't reliable there, because Windows machines have bash now, and lots of people use it as their shell).

Re-opening, if anyone wants to adapt that code above into a PR and add some way to check for the executing shell (maybe just look at `process.env.SHELL` or `process.env.BASH_VERSION` or something?) that'd be lovely. (Tests and docs also nice.)

