With promises and the async/await pattern now firmly established both in the browser and Node.js (not to mention https://deno.land now being a thing), it would be quite useful if `glob` supported the modern `async` pattern by returning a promise, in addition to still honoring the callback if specified, e.g.:

```
function glob(pattern, callback) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    whateverTheInternalCodeCallsAre(pattern, (err, files) => {
      if (callback) {
        callback(err, files);
      }
      if (err) {
        reject(err);
      } else {
        resolve(files);
      }
    });
  });
}
```

(and of course, "people can just write this themselves", but there would be _tremendous_ value in the library doing this for everyone, instead of thousands of people all having to roll that same code over and over)

