issues.body:
Re #375

For streaming and iteration walkers, support `nounique:true`, to avoid _any_ long-term caching of anything.  That would mean, no `seen` set of matches, and investigate the `Processor` classes to ensure that nothing is being cached indefinitely.  (Pretty sure it's not an issue, because each directory walk only inherits the HasWalkedCache from its parent but doesn't share with siblings, so you _should_ never have a case where it grows particularly large.)

Because PathScurry uses an lru cache to store child path objects, this would mean that it's possible to walk arbitrarily large file systems and iterate over their results, with streams or iterators and `nounique:true`.  The caveat would be that you _may_ get duplicate entries if the pattern contains certain combinations of `**` and/or `..`, but that's probably fine.

Obviously, the `glob()`, `globSync()`, `Glob.walk()` and `Glob.walkSync()` methods will effectively always be unique-ified, and subject to blowing up on massive walks, because they gather up results in a Set and return them all at once in an array.  But for very large folder structures, it might still be worth doing, if you have a pattern like `**/needle.txt` where there's only 1 `needle.txt` in a folder structure with a million files, because even though the _matches_ are unique, we don't have to ensure that the _walks_ are never repeated.

Alternatively, could store `seen` in an LRUCache, but that's quite a bit slower than just using a Set.  Maybe another approach there would be a sort of "forgetful set"?

```ts
// only store up to n items
class ForgetfulSet<T> extends Set<T> {
  max: number
  count: number
  constructor (max: number) {
    super()
    this.max = max
    // only needed if tracking this.count is faster than using this.size
    this.count = 0
  }
  // only needed if tracking this.count is faster than using this.size
  delete (v: T) {
    if (this.has(v)) {
      this.count --
    }
    return super.delete(v)
  }
  add(v: T) {
    // only needed if tracking this.count is faster than using this.size
    this.count ++
    if (this.count > this.max) {
      for (const v of this) {
        this.delete(v)
        break
      }
    }
    return super.add(v)
  }
}
```

Checking `size` on every set might be cheap enough to not need the `count` number.  Benchmark it.

